Maybe I can show you my problem with this issue, on this example:

We have a piece of code:
```
public Set<Date> getADateInASet(Date date) {
        Set<Date> hashSet = new HashSet<>();
        hashSet.add(date);
        return hashSet;
    }
```

If someone changes it unexpectedly to this:

```
public Set<Date> getADateInASet(Date date) {
        Set<Date> hashSet = new HashSet<>();
        hashSet.add(date);
        date.setTime(123L); // unexpected change (yes, bad practice, but can happen)
        return hashSet;
    } 
```

my test:

```
@Test
    public void testDoesNotNoticeThatProductionCodeHasChanged() throws Exception {
        HashSetWrapper a = new HashSetWrapper();
        Date date = new Date();
        Set<Date> hashSet = a.getADateInASet(date);

        Assertions.assertThat(hashSet).contains(date); //For second code example, this should fail
    }
```

should fail, because the code will definately fail in production. This issue is not detected before someone executes the code. I don¬¥t appreciate this.
Shouldn¬¥t this be the reason to write tests? Something should fail in tests aswell, if it fails in production.
